The surface termination and reconstruction of nickel phosphides as well as the active role of P atoms during the electrochemical processes have been thoroughly investigated using DFT calculations by Wexler et al.342. They found that the surface P content on Ni2P(0001) depends on the external electrode potential, i.e., at −0.21 V ≥ U ≥ −0.36 V versus the standard hydrogen electrode and pH = 0, and a PHx-enriched Ni3P2 termination is most stable for Ni2P(0001), while beyond this potential range, the Ni3P2 surface is passivated by H at the Ni3-hollow sites. In contrast, Ni5P4(0001¯\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
